Myopathies

#2021BSQ-NOV/Q01

The typical presentation of a myopathy is:

Symmetrical
proximal muscle weakness, (i.e large muscles get inflamed more?)
wasting, (?inflmmation causes wasting somehow?)
normal sensation, and normal stretch reflexes. (neurology is intact)

Timeline of presentation

  • Acquired myopathies present in an acute or subacute fashion.
  • Inherited myopathies present with chronic symptoms (with the exception of metabolic myopathies) where symptoms can be acutely precipitated.

Causes of myopathy:

  • Inflammatory:
    • [[2021 General Medicine July#Polymyositis and dermatomyositis|dermatomyositis and polymyositis]], inclusion body myositis,
  • Endocrine:
    • Hypothyroidism, Cushing's
  • Electrolyte disorders
  • Metabolic myopathies:
    • carbohydrate, lipid, purine metabolic disorders
  • Drugs:
    • Cocaine, heroin, alcohol, glucocorticoids,
  • Infections - all sorts of viruses
  • Rhabodymyolysis - of various causes

Vasopressin like drugs

#2021SBR-JUL/Q03

Vasopressin physiology:
3 classes of receptors for vasopressin:

  • V1a - Vasoconstriction
  • V1b - ACTH release
  • V2 (in basolateral membrane of DCT and collecting duct)- Antidiuretic response

Vasopressin antagonists:
Tolvaptan - Oral V2 antagonist -> causes free water loss
Conivaptan - IV antagonist of V2 and V1a.

Vasopressin agonists:

Vasopressin Desmopressin Terlipressin felypressin
Short duration Longer duration Longer duration Short acting
Weakly V2 selective V2 selective V1: mainly pressor action vasocontrictor
☝️Less pressor action minimal V2 action Used to prolong local anaesthetic action

Carbon dioxide transport

  • Carbaminohaemoglobin is the molecule formed with Carbon dioxide binds haemoglobin. 23% of CO2 in the blood is transported this way. 70% is transpoted as bicarbonate and 7 as free CO2).

Effects of CO2 on haemoglobin:

  • more CO2 binds Hb at lower oxygen saturation facillitating CO2 removal from hypoxic tissues.

    • because deoxygenated haemoglobin has higher affinity for CO2.

  • Conversely, bound CO2 is release from haemoglobin when it becomes oxygenated.

  • Haldane effect: Source

"The Haldane effect is the difference in the quantity of carbon dioxide carried, at constant PCO2, in oxygenated (less CO2) and deoxygenated blood (More CO2)".

  • One component is due to increased deoxyhaemoglobin affinity for CO2. (70% of Haldane effect)
  • Deoxyhaemoglobin is more basic -> more HCO3 is formed within red cells -> i.e more CO2 is converted to HCO3 and transported as HCO3. (30% of Haldane effect)

Bohr effect: Source

The decrease in the oxygen affinity of haemoglobin in the presence of low pH or high CO2

Methaemoglobin

Search: methemoglobin

Normal Hb has Fe2+; If Fe2+ gets oxidised to Fe3+, methaemoglobin is formed.
The Fe3+ haem doesn't bind O2 but increases the affinity of the other haems for O2. There is resultant left shift of the dissociation curve causing functional anaemia.

Cyanosis is common in methaemoglobinaemia.

Causes of methemoglobinemia

Hereditary :

  • Cytochrom b5 reductase deficiency - majority
  • Haemoglobin M disease and cytochrome b5 deficiency
  • cytochrom b5 deficiency

Acquired:

  • Dapsone : common cause- even topical treatment - (Treatment of leprosy, also used for [[2021 General Medicine July#Deramatologic manifestations of internal malignancy|Sweet syndrome]], acne)
  • nitrates and nitrites
  • Inhaled nitric oxide (unusual at inhaled therapeutic range)
  • nitrates and nitrite (sodium nitrite is a food preservative)
  • Rasburicase - recombinant urate oxidase used to treat hyperurucaemia in maglinancy and tumor lysis syndrome.

Assessment

Pulse oxymetry - pulse oximeters will show a an erroneous saturation of 85% because of the absorptive spectrum of methhaemoglobin.

- Management: similar to normal hyponatremia in SIADH; Free water restriction, Demeclocycline - decreases renal response to ADH, ADH receptor antagonists (conivaptan, tolvaptan).
  • If water restriction not tolerated, demeclocycline (ADH antagonist - causes #photosensitive rash!)

B12 deficiency

Glossitis + angular stomatitis + neuropathy
#2021SBR-JUL/Q01
Features of B12 defieciency neuropathy:

  • Neuropathic features are commoner in B12 deficiency than in B9 deficiency.
  • posterior columns first -> then lateral columns
  • Neuropathy is symmetrical, involves legs > arms and causes paraesthesia and gait problems.
  • The classic finding is subacute combined dengeneration of the spinal cord.
    • This leads to demyelination of the dorsal and lateral white matter. (i.e tracts).
    • Leading to sensory (paraesthesia, sensory ataxia) and motor (weakness, spacticity, paraplegia and incontinence).

No aphasia ; but anarthria

Venous sinus thrombosis (Cerebral venous thrombosis CVT)

#2021SBR-JUL/Q04
Presentation can be acute, subacute or chronic.
Mean age of onset - 39 years!
Major risk factors:

  • Prothrombotic conditions - Protein C / S deficiency, factor V leiden etc.
  • OCP, pregnancy, puerperium, malignancy, obesity, head injury and mechanical precipitants.

Pathogenesis of symptoms:

  • Obstructed venous drainage causes obstruction of
    • venous blood flow -> increased capillary pressure -> stroke and disruption of blood brain barrier.
    • CSF drainage -> increased intracranial pressure.

Symptom groups:

  • Isolated intracranial hypertension syndrome
    • (headache (the commonest symptoms CVT) +/- vomiting, papilloedema and visual problems )
  • focal syndrome (focal deficits - especially if not fitting a vascular distribution and or seizures)
    • Weakness with monoparesis or hemiparesis, sometimes bilateral is the most frequent focal deficit in CVT.
  • Encephalopathy (multifocal signs, mental status changes and stupor or coma)

Less common presentations:

  • Cavernous sinus syndrome [[Neurology Miscellaneous#Cavernous sinus anatomy]]
  • SAH
  • multiple cranial nerve palsies.

Hydroxycarbamide (hydroxyurea) works by increasing HbF levels; given to all patients.

[!INFO] upper left image shows increased cup - disk ratio in glaucoma; not relevant to papilloedema

Treatment: prophylactic prehydration, allopurinol (xanthine oxidase inhibitor and Rasburicase - recombinant urate oxidase)
